\f0\fs24 \cf0 A few things need to be kept in mind while applying this MenuPackage\
\
1. First of all go to the BuildSettings of your project and arrange the scenes in following order:\
	\
  a) Splash\
  b) MenuScene\
  c) loadingScene\
  c) Your Scene (as many as you want)\
  d) PlayAgain\
  e) levelSelect(if you are going for different levels in your game)\
\
2. Apply "
\b loadSettings.js
\b0 " and "
\b pauseGame.js
\b0 " scripts to an empty GameObject in your scene(s). To make it more convenient, i have made a prefab by the name of Settings, so you can just drag it in your scene and ready to go.\
\
3. Provide 
\b OrangeGUISkin
\b0  to the 
\b GUISkin
\b0  field of every script (if they are empty) in the inspector view.\
\
4. Provide the name of the scene you want to load in the field "
\b sceneToLoad
\b0 " in the inspector view to PlayAgain script (in the PlayAgain Scene)\
\
5. It has now included 2 new levels viz., 
\b loading
\b0  and 
\b levelSelect. 
\b0  You can drag them in your build settings according to your need.\
\
6. For the 
\b levelSelect
\b0  scene, name your levels in numbers i.e., 1,2,3,\'85 so on. It will automatically load scenes accordingly. Ofcourse you can always modify the script as per your need.\
\
7. For the 
\b loadingScene
\b0  just drag it before any level which you want to load and want to show the loading screen just before it gets loaded. It will automatically load that scene\
\
8. 
\b pauseGame
\b0  script has been simplified down into functions to support the functionality with EZGUI. Now you can drag the script onto a gameObject and then assign this object to the EZGUI control and name the method you want to call.\
\
For example, if you have a pause button in your scene made with EZGUI and a gameObject viz. Script, then drag the pauseGame script onto the 
\b Script
\b0  
\b Object
\b0  and assign this gameObject to the ScriptWithMethodToInvoke and the method name as 
\b pause
\b0 . Now when you hit the button it shall call the pause method and your game will be paused.\
\
